"This was an obligement never to be forgotten ; and the more to be considered, because antecedent to her love. That passion, it is true, produced the usual effects of generosity, gallantry, and care to please ; and thither we refer them. But, when she had made all these advances, it was still in his power to have refused them: after the intrigue of the cave (call it marriage, or enjoyment only), he was no longer free to take or leave ; he had accepted the favour, and was obliged to be constant, if he â€˜would be grateful."